{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486730"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:43:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"165"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/165"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.33,0.26,0.35,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"165"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101638"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/165"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"165"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84079"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44326"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101638"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department with an eight-hour history of headache and mild fever, accompanied by nausea and photophobia. The headache came on gradually at lunchtime and has continued to worsen. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a university student living in shared accommodation and plays competitive netball. She denies illicit drug use or alcohol consumption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly unwell. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 118/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. She is alert and oriented but appears slightly irritable. There is mild nuchal rigidity and Kernig\u0027s and Brudzinski\u0027s signs are negative. Her neurological examination reveals no focal deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 10.2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 7.2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (2.0-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 15 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause for her presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epidural haematoma","Bacterial meningitis","Atypical migraine","Viral encephalitis","Cluster headache"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDespite relatively mild symptoms and borderline inflammatory markers, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebacterial meningitis\u003C/strong\u003E remains the most likely diagnosis and most important to exclude. Early bacterial meningitis can present with subtle signs, and the absence of marked fever or severe meningism should not exclude the diagnosis. The combination of new onset headache, photophobia, and even subtle neck stiffness in a young adult should prompt consideration of meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidural haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents following head trauma, which is possible in a netball player. However, this type of headache usually presents with a lucid interval followed by deteriorating consciousness, and the presence of fever makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtypical migraine\u003C/strong\u003E could present with similar symptoms including gradual onset headache, photophobia, and nausea. However, the presence of fever would be unusual. The absence of any previous headache history also makes migraine less likely as a first presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral encephalitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with more prominent altered mental status, confusion, or focal neurological signs. While fever is common, the preservation of normal consciousness and absence of focal neurological signs make this diagnosis less likely. Herpes simplex encephalitis, the most serious form, usually presents with more severe alterations in consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECluster headache\u003C/strong\u003E presents with severe, unilateral periorbital pain typically lasting 15-180 minutes, often with autonomic features such as lacrimation or rhinorrhoea. The gradual onset, bilateral nature, and presence of fever make this an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key learning point is that early bacterial meningitis may present with relatively mild symptoms and normal or only slightly abnormal inflammatory markers. The threshold for performing lumbar puncture should be low when headache, fever, and any degree of neck stiffness are present, even if subtle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Recent onset of headache with associated nuchal rigidity makes bacterial meningitis the diagnosis to be excluded.","The presence of normal neurological examination and absence of altered consciousness helps differentiate meningitis from encephalitis.","Fever, meningism and raised inflammatory markers may be absent in early bacterial meningitis."],"references":["van de Beek D, de Gans J, Spanjaard L, Weisfelt M, Reitsma JB, Vermeulen M. Clinical features and prognostic factors in adults with bacterial meningitis. N Engl J Med [Internet]. 2004 Oct 28 [cited 2025 May 2];351(18):1849\u201359. Available from: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa040845","Hasbun R. Clinical features and diagnosis of acute bacterial meningitis in adults [Internet]. UpToDate; 2020 [cited 2025 May 2]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-features-and-diagnosis-of-acute-bacterial-meningitis-in-adults","Gluckman S. Viral encephalitis in adults [Internet]. UpToDate; 2019 [cited 2025 May 2]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/viral-encephalitis-in-adults","Singer R, Ogilvy C, Rordorf G. Aneurysmal subarachnoid hemorrhage: Clinical manifestations and diagnosis [Internet]. UpToDate; 2020 [cited 2025 May 2]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/aneurysmal-subarachnoid-hemorrhage-clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis","Wong E, Wu J. Overview of the clinical features and diagnosis of brain tumors in adults [Internet]. UpToDate; 2019 [cited 2025 May 2]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/overview-of-the-clinical-features-and-diagnosis-of-brain-tumors-in-adults"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84079"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"165"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84079"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T15:33:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-03T15:34:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"165"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101638"}}},"meta":{"can